com.ibm.xmi.framework
Interface XMIClass

All Superinterfaces:
Classifier, Data
All Known Implementing Classes:
XMIClassImpl
public interface XMIClass
extends Classifier

This interface represents a class; in most object-oriented systems, you can make instances of classes. In the framework, you can set the definer of an XMI object to its class, and you can add an XMI object that is an instance of an XMI class to the class using the addXMIDefined method, which is declared in the Data interface.

An XMIClass is one kind of Classifier; a Datatype is the other kind.

You use framework classes to create XMI DTDs and schemas and to create models that define XMI objects.

Framework classes have superclasses and subclasses. The methods in this interface let you add and delete superclasses and subclasses from a class and get the direct superclasses and subclasses. To get all superclasses and subclasses for a class, you need to get the direct superclasses or subclasses, then get the superclasses or subclasses for those classes, etc.

Multiple inheritance is allowed.

Classes inherit features from superclasses, although you need to traverse all superclasses to obtain the features for a given class; the framework interface methods only return local features for a given class.

The features of a class define the legal values for XMI objects that represent instances of the class. A Value of an object must have a corresponding feature in its class to be semantically correct; the framework does not enforce this, though.

You can create a Feature whose type is an XMIClass and whose value type is Value.OBJECT to represent what used to be object properties in previous Framework versions.

You can create features whose types are XMIClasses and whose value types are one of Value.REFERENCE, Value.CONTAINER, or Value.CONTAIN to represent links in previous versions of the Framework.

The framework will create framework classes for you from UML 1.1 XMI 1.0 files. Please see the DeclarationFactory class for more details.

The features of classes that are relevant for the framework are the structural features that define the valid state of XMI objects. You may notice that the framework object model does not include behavior for classes or objects; this is a deliberate omission. Only the state of XMI objects is stored in XMI files, not the behavior of the objects. Of course, you can model the behavior of objects in your models if you wish. For example, you can create a model in the framework corresponding to UML, which defines operations and methods for UML classes and UML instances.
